<p><i><b>Guns, Germs, and Steel: The Fates of Human Societies</b></i> is a 1997 book by <a href="/wiki/Jared_Diamond" title="Jared Diamond">Jared Diamond</a>, professor of <a href="/wiki/Geography" title="Geography">geography</a> and <a href="/wiki/Physiology" title="Physiology">physiology</a> at <a href="/wiki/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles" title="University of California, Los Angeles">UCLA</a>. In 1998 it won a <a href="/wiki/Pulitzer_Prize" title="Pulitzer Prize">Pulitzer Prize</a> and the <a href="/wiki/The_Aventis_Prizes_for_Science_Books" title="The Aventis Prizes for Science Books" class="mw-redirect">Aventis Prize for Best Science Book</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Documentary_film" title="Documentary film">documentary</a> based on the <a href="/wiki/Book" title="Book">book</a> was <a href="/wiki/Broadcast" title="Broadcast" class="mw-redirect">broadcast</a> on <a href="/wiki/Public_Broadcasting_Service" title="Public Broadcasting Service">PBS</a> in July 2005, produced by the <a href="/wiki/National_Geographic_Society" title="National Geographic Society">National Geographic Society</a>.</p>
